.TH "CSSMEDIARULE.MEDIA" "3JS" "November 25, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
CSSMediaRule.media \- CSSMediaRule: media property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The read\-only \f[B]\f[CB]media\f[B]\f[R] property of the
\f[CR]CSSMediaRule\f[R] interface contains a \f[CR]MediaList\f[R] object
representing the media query list of the \f[CR]\(atmedia\f[R] rule.
.SH VALUE
A \f[CR]MediaList\f[R] object.
.PP
Although the \f[CR]media\f[R] property itself is read\-only in the sense
that you can\(cqt replace the \f[CR]MediaList\f[R] object, you can still
assign to the \f[CR]media\f[R] property directly, which is equivalent to
assigning to its \f[CR]mediaText\f[R] property.
You can also modify the \f[CR]MediaList\f[R] object using the
\f[CR]appendMedium()\f[R] and \f[CR]deleteMedium()\f[R] methods.
.SH EXAMPLES
The CSS includes a media query with one style rule.
This will be the first \f[CR]CSSRule\f[R] returned by
\f[CR]document.styleSheets[0].cssRules\f[R].
Calling \f[CR]myRules[0].media\f[R] therefore returns a
\f[CR]MediaList\f[R] object representing the media query.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]\(atmedia\f[R] (\f[B]width\f[R] >= 500px) {
  body {
    \f[B]color\f[R]: blue;
  }
}
.EE
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] myRules = document.styleSheets[0].cssRules;
console.log(myRules[0].media); \f[I]// a MediaList\f[R]
.EE
